From 60d4c8dc0b0059c752ad8d2ab702f8762a52628b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 15:57:04 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 10/11] Start listed child servers when a server reaches its
 steady trigger

A single Wings node routinely runs servers that depend on one another. The
motivating case: two Soulmask instances share a read-only ramdisk holding the
bind-mounted install content. One instance owns the update (AUTO_UPDATE=1); the
other (AUTO_UPDATE=0) depends on the owner's steamcmd writes having propagated
through the shared mount. If the dependent instance starts while the owner's
update is still in flight it can read a half-written file. The general shape is
ordinary cluster start-ordering: a client that must not come up until its main
is confirmed ready.

Add WINGS_CG_CHILD_SERVERS, an admin-only per-server list of OTHER server UUIDs
on this node. When THIS server reaches its steady trigger, Wings attempts to
start each listed child. It deliberately piggybacks on the existing
WINGS_CG_STEADY_MATCH event (server/slice_phase.go enterSteady) rather than on
plain "started": the steady trigger only fires once the server is genuinely up,
which for an update-on-boot server is after the update has completed -- so a
dependent server gated on it never races a half-written install.

Design points, all of which fail safe:

- NOT honoured on the grace-timer backstop. A trigger that never fired means
  readiness was never confirmed -- pulled out as its own named predicate,
  childStartEligible, so the exclusion has a unit test that does not need a
  live Environment.

- Fire-and-forget on its own goroutine (server/slice_children.go), so
  resolving and starting children never delays the triggering server's own
  phase transition or console processing.

- Idempotent and defensive. Each child is started through HandlePowerAction,
  the exact path the Panel/API start uses. A suspended child, a UUID not
  managed by this node, or a server listing itself is logged and skipped.
  resolveChildServers is kept pure (never calls HandlePowerAction itself) so
  the resolution/skip logic is unit-testable with a bare *Manager and *Server
  values, with no Environment/Docker involved -- the same split
  applySliceProps already uses against cgroups.EnsureForServer, rather than a
  package-level test-seam variable (this codebase's existing pattern for a
  side effect that genuinely needs Docker/systemd is a build-tag-gated
  integration test, e.g. internal/cgroups/integration_test.go, not a seam in
  the production call graph).

Servers reach their siblings through a new set-once back-reference to the
owning Manager, wired in Manager.InitServer before the server is used; nil for
servers built outside a manager (unit tests), every read guards against that.
Parsing (cgroups.ChildServersFromEnv) accepts comma- or newline-separated
UUIDs, mirroring the multi-entry convention of the other WINGS_CG_* list
variables, and de-duplicates.

Two correctness gaps closed before this could be trusted:

- WINGS_CG_STEADY_MATCH was only compiled/armed when a startup memory band was
  also staged (beginSlicePhase bailed out before reaching the matcher when
  Staged() was false). A server with an explicit trigger but no band therefore
  had it silently ignored, and the phase ended on the egg's own done/running
  line instead -- exactly the gap a child-gating trigger cannot afford. The
  matcher (and, behind it, the startup_grace backstop) is now armed whenever
  either a band is staged OR an explicit trigger is configured; a node using
  neither still arms nothing, so this is not a regression for the common case
  (TestBeginSlicePhaseOnlyArmsWhenStaged still passes unchanged;
  TestBeginSlicePhaseArmsMatcherWithoutStagedBand is the new coverage).

- Wings' own boot sequence (cmd/root.go) previously restored every server
  whose persisted state was running/starting by calling HandlePowerAction
  directly, with no awareness of WINGS_CG_CHILD_SERVERS -- so a parent and
  child both running across a reboot would be started concurrently by that
  same boot sequence, reintroducing the exact race this feature exists to
  prevent. The boot sequence now probes every server's live container state
  in its own pass first, then (cgroups.DeferBootRestart) defers a child's
  direct restart whenever its configured parent is ALSO being restored this
  boot: the parent's restart replays the ordinary HandlePowerAction path,
  which refires its console listener and therefore its steady trigger exactly
  as it would at runtime, and that is what starts the child -- no new
  waiting/timeout machinery, just not racing it a second time here. A cyclic
  or mutual child relationship cannot supply a server that starts unprompted,
  so it is left unsuppressed (fails open, same as resolveChildServers does at
  runtime) rather than risk every member of the cycle staying offline forever.

Remaining, deliberate limitation (documented, not solved in code): if a
child's parent is stopped while the child keeps running, then an operator
starts the child by hand, it autostarts unconditionally like any other server
on the next reboot with no parent to wait for -- Wings has no dedicated "do
not autostart" flag. Keeping a child stopped whenever its parent is stopped is
the operator's responsibility; see the EnvChildServers doc comment and
SETUP.md.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
